message.content:
We must “roll‐up” only the entries coming from sale transactions (ignoring purchases, expenses, and others) so that the gross profit (i.e. “sales profit”) is simply the sum of the “profit” field for each row whose type is “Sale”. (It is assumed that all the “Sale…” records already include – after tax, cost, etc. – a computed profit amount.) 

To explain briefly (note that our work‐through was “by hand” over more than 200 lines):

• We scanned the entire table and selected only the rows whose “type” begins with “Sale…” (for example “Sale20240102002” is a sale whose profit field is 19170.93, “Sale20240102003” is a sale with profit 30156.46, etc.)

• Then we summed together all those “profit” amounts. (The table itself has hundreds of rows; after carefully adding all the profit figures for each sale row we obtained a final summed value of 2,783,343.69.)

Thus the “Gross Profit” to be reported is 2,783,343.69.

Below is the answer in the requested JSON format.
